EN.STORE_PROFILE_ANNUALIZED_RETURN_TOOLTIP: One Year total return. It is updated daily. Higher is better. It should be clear that the past performance is not a guarantee of future results.
EN.STORE_PROFILE_ANNUALIZED_VOLATILITY_TOOL: It is the Risk measure. It is calculated using daily geometric returns then it is annualized. Lower is better as it means that ticker daily change is less volatile. Annualized volatility is a measure for market risk.
EN.STORE_PROFILE_ANN_RETUN_CHART_TOOLTIP: Annualized compound total return in the indicated period. For e.g. if 6 months total return is 1%, then the annualized return for 6 months is 2.02%. It should be clear that the past performance is not a guarantee of future results.
EN.STORE_PROFILE_EXPECTED_GROWTH_TOOLTIP: Average expected growth is evaluated based on historical 1Y growth. Best and Worst values are the expected values for investing 1,000 to satisfy a confidence interval of 68.3% probability based on the past year performance and volatility. It should be clear that past performance is not a guarantee of future results.
EN.STORE_PROFILE_MINIMUM_INVESTMENT_TOOLTIP: Minimum amount to buy this ticker.
EN.STORE_PROFILE_RISK_CHART_TOOLTIP: Risk rank is a proxy for market risk associated with this ticker compared to other tickers in the store. It's not an absolute measure for risk.
EN.STORE_PROFILE_SHARP_RATIO_TOOLTIP: Sharpe ratio is a measure of return earned in excess of the risk-free rate with respect to risk. Higher Sharpe ratio means either higher return or less risk. Higher is better.
EN.STORE_PROFILE_TOT_RETURN_PERF_TOOLTIP: Total return includes both capital appreciation (Increase/decrease in unit price) and distributed dividends.
EN.STORE_SUMMARY_TOOLTIP_5: Mutual fund is an investment vehicle managed by a professional asset manager to match the investment objectives by investing in some instruments.
EN.STORE_SUMMARY_TOOLTIP_51: ETFs are Exchange Traded Funds. Underlying assets are decided by the asset manager. It is like mutual funds but it is cheaper in trading.
EN.STORE_SUMMARY_TOOLTIP_52: Investment strategy is a portfolio that is made of some traded instruments in specific weights to achieve a defined mandate.

EN.US_ASSET_TURNOVER_TOOLTIP: Measures a company’s ability to generate sales from assets and a higher ratio than the industry average indicates the company generates sales more efficiently than the industry
EN.US_AUGMENTING_MSG: Shown Level 2 order book has best bid and best offer from multiple exchanges (Level 1) and Nasdaq TotalView Level two details.
EN.US_CURRENT_RATIO_TOOLTIP: Measures a company’s ability to pay short-term obligations using it’s short term assets. A ratio higher than the industry average indicates the company’s short-term liquidity is stronger than the industry
EN.US_DIV_GROWTH_TOOLTIP: Measures the average growth rate of dividends paid by the company over a 5 year period
EN.US_DIV_YIELD_TOOLTIP: Compares dividend paid by the company to its stock price and a higher ratio is considered better
EN.US_EN_VAL_CASH_FLOW_TOOLTIP: Compares the total valuation of the company with its ability to generate cashflow. Lower the ratio the faster the company can generate cash to reinvest in its business
EN.US_EPS_GROWTH_TOOLTIP: Measures the average growth rate of company’s earnings per share over a 5 year period
EN.US_INV_TURNOVER_TOOLTIP: Measures how many times a company’s inventory is sold and replaced over a trailing 12 month period and a higher value than the industry average is considered better
EN.US_LNG_TERM_DEBT_EQ_TOOLTIP: Indicates the ratio of long-term debt to shareholder’s equity and a lower ratio is considered better as it indicates the company is financed with less debt and more equity
EN.US_NET_INT_CVG_TOOLTIP: Measures a company’s ability to meet it’s net interest payments from it’s earnings. A higher ratio than the industry average is considered better
EN.US_NET_PROF_MARGIN_TOOLTIP: Compares net income of a company to its sales to determine how much profit the company is making after paying all expenses. Higher ratio than the industry average indicates company is more efficient at converting sales to profit
EN.US_PB_RATIO_TOOLTIP: Compares a company’s stock price to it’s most recent quarterly book value per share. Lower P/B Ratio is cosidered better as it indicates the stock is undervalued (stock is trading at a discount its book value)
EN.US_PE_RATIO_TOOLTIP: Compares a company’s stock price to it’s TTM earnings per share. Lower P/E Ratio is cosidered better as it indicates the stock is undervalued (stock is trading lower compared to its fundamentals)
EN.US_QUICK_RATIO_TOOLTIP: Measures a company’s ability to pay short-term obligations using it’s short term assets excluding inventory. A ratio higher than the industry average indicates company’s short-term liquidity is stronger than the industry
EN.US_RCV_TURNOVER_TOOLTIP: Measures how many times a company can turn receivables into cash over a trailing 12 month period and a higher value than the industry average is considered better
EN.US_REV_GROWTH_TOOLTIP: Measures the average growth rate of company’s revenue over a 5 year period
EN.US_ROE_TOOLTIP: Measures how efficiently a company is using its shareholders equity to generate profit and a ratio higher than the industry average is considered better
EN.US_ROI_TOOLTIP: Measures how efficiently a company is using its total investments to generate profit and a ratio higher than the industry average is considered better
EN.US_TOTAL_DEBT_EQUI_TOOLTIP: Indicates the ratio of debt to shareholder’s equity and a lower ratio is considered better as it indicates the company is financed with less debt and more equity
EN.US_TREND_TOOLTIP: It shows total return over selected period compared to previous similar period. Values are updated by end of the day.
